The nominations for the 76th Primetime Emmy Awards were announced on July 17, 2024, in a virtual broadcast originating from the [[El Capitan Theatre]] in [[Hollywood, Los Angeles|Hollywood]], Los Angeles, hosted by actor [[Tony Hale]], actress [[Sheryl Lee Ralph]] and Television Academy chair [[Cris Abrego]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2024/06/emmy-awards-tony-hale-sheryl-lee-ralph-to-announce-nominees-1235985546/ |title=Emmy Awards: Tony Hale & Sheryl Lee Ralph to Announce Nominees |last=Petski |first=Denise |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=June 28, 2024 |access-date=June 28, 2024 |archive-date=June 28, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240628145203/https://deadline.com/2024/06/emmy-awards-tony-hale-sheryl-lee-ralph-to-announce-nominees-1235985546/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Including nominations at the [[76th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]], ''[[Shōgun (2024 TV series)|Shōgun]]'' led all programs with 25 nominations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2024/tv/news/2024-emmy-nominations-list-1236074176/ |title=Emmy Nominations 2024: ''Shogun'' Leads All Shows with 25 Nods, ''The Bear'' Close Behind with 23 |last1=Moreau |first1=Jordan |last2=Schneider |first2=Michael |last3=Ramos Bechara |first3=Diego |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 17, 2024 |access-date=July 17, 2024 |archive-date=July 17, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240717181656/https://variety.com/2024/tv/news/2024-emmy-nominations-list-1236074176/ |url-status=live}}</ref> It was also the second non-English language series to be nominated for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]] after ''[[Squid Game]]'', which was nominated [[74th Primetime Emmy Awards|two years earlier]].<ref name="History">{{cite news |last=Brzeski |first=Patrick |title=''Shogun'' Makes History with 25 Emmy Nominations |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/shogun-historical-25-emmy-nominations-2024-diversity-1235949510/ |access-date=September 21, 2024 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 17, 2024 |archive-date=October 7, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241007182236/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/shogun-historical-25-emmy-nominations-2024-diversity-1235949510/ |url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Bear (TV series)|The Bear]]'' became the most-nominated comedy series for a single season in the awards' history with 23 nominations; the program surpassed the record held by the [[NBC]] comedy ''[[30 Rock]]'', which received 22 nominations in [[61st Primetime Emmy Awards|2009]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/the-bear-breaks-30-rock-record-comedy-emmy-nominations/ |title=''The Bear'' Breaks ''30 Rock'' Emmy Record for Most Nominations in a Comedy Series |last=Ng |first=Philiana |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=July 17, 2024 |access-date=July 17, 2024 |archive-date=July 17, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240717195236/https://www.thewrap.com/the-bear-breaks-30-rock-record-comedy-emmy-nominations/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2024/tv/awards/the-bear-emmys-comedy-nomination-record-1236062449/ |title=''The Bear'' Breaks Emmy Record for Comedy Series with 23 Nominations |last=Davis |first=Clayton |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 17, 2024 |access-date=July 17, 2024 |archive-date=July 18, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240718012221/https://variety.com/2024/tv/awards/the-bear-emmys-comedy-nomination-record-1236062449/ |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Lily Gladstone]] of the series ''[[Under the Bridge (TV series)|Under the Bridge]]'' and [[Kali Reis]] of the series ''[[True Detective season 4|True Detective: Night Country]]'' became the first indigenous American women to receiving acting nominations; along with [[D'Pharaoh Woon-A-Tai]] of the series ''[[Reservation Dogs]]'', they were the first indigenous American actors to earn an acting nomination since [[August Schellenberg]] for his role in the television film ''[[Bury My Heart at Wounded Knee (film)|Bury My Heart at Wounded Knee]]'' in [[59th Primetime Emmy Awards|2007]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Ng |first=Philiana |title=Lily Gladstone, D'Pharaoh Woon-A-Tai, Kali Reis Are First Indigenous Actors in 17 Years to Land Emmy Nominations |url=https://www.thewrap.com/lily-gladstone-emmy-nomination-under-the-bridge/ |access-date=September 24, 2024 |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=July 17, 2024 |archive-date=September 29, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240929075917/https://www.thewrap.com/lily-gladstone-emmy-nomination-under-the-bridge/ |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Netflix]] led all networks and platforms with 107 nominations. [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] came in second place with 93 nominations, surpassing its own record of 56 nominations in [[68th Primetime Emmy Awards|2016]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2024/07/emmys-2024-nominations-netflix-fx-hbo-1236012372/ |title=Netflix Leads Total Emmy Nominations But FX Comes in Close Second with Record Haul Ahead of HBO |last=White |first=Peter |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=July 17, 2024 |access-date=July 17, 2024 |archive-date=July 17, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240717165335/https://deadline.com/2024/07/emmys-2024-nominations-netflix-fx-hbo-1236012372/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

The winners were announced on September 15, following the Creative Arts Emmys on September 7 and 8. With 36 total wins, FX led all networks and platforms for the first time.<ref name="Network Tally">{{cite news |last=Otterson |first=Joe |title=FX Wins Most Emmys of 2024 as ''Shogun'' and ''The Bear'' Top Night |url=https://variety.com/2024/tv/awards/emmys-2024-fx-most-wins-network-shogun-the-bear-1236139779/ |access-date=September 21, 2024 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 15, 2024 |archive-date=September 21, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240921074042/https://variety.com/2024/tv/awards/emmys-2024-fx-most-wins-network-shogun-the-bear-1236139779/ |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Shōgun'' became the first non-English-language series to win Outstanding Drama Series and won a total of 18 awards, breaking the record of 13 set by ''[[John Adams (miniseries)|John Adams]]'' in [[60th Primetime Emmy Awards|2008]] to become the most awarded program for a single year in Emmy history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2024/awards/news/shogun-breaks-emmy-record-most-wins-1236138477/ |title=''Shogun'' Shatters Emmy Record with 18 Wins in One Season |last=Tangcay |first=Jazz |date=September 15, 2024 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=September 18, 2024 |archive-date=September 17, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240917185155/https://variety.com/2024/awards/news/shogun-breaks-emmy-record-most-wins-1236138477/ |url-status=live}}</ref> It also passed ''[[Game of Thrones]]''{{'}}s 12 wins in [[67th Primetime Emmy Awards|2015]], 2016, and [[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|2019]] for most wins by a drama series in a single season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title=''Shōgun'' Caps Record Emmy Run with Win No. 18 for Outstanding Drama Series as Star Hiroyuki Sanada Pays Homage to Samurai Period Dramas |url=https://www.thewrap.com/shogun-new-record-most-emmy-wins-single-season-2024/ |access-date=September 21, 2024 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=September 15, 2024 |archive-date=September 21, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240921075056/https://www.thewrap.com/shogun-new-record-most-emmy-wins-single-season-2024/ |url-status=live}}</ref> With its 11 wins, ''The Bear'' surpassed its own record for most wins for a comedy series in a single year. For their work on ''Shōgun'', [[Hiroyuki Sanada]] and [[Anna Sawai]] were the first Japanese performers to win [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]], respectively.<ref name="History"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/article/emmy-shogun-japan-samurai-series-award-3fbc80c598664d09274cdbe80ed511d5 |title=Japan celebrates record Emmy wins for ''Shogun'' |last=Kageyama |first=Yuri |date=September 16, 2024 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=September 18, 2024 |archive-date=September 19, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240919005032/https://apnews.com/article/emmy-shogun-japan-samurai-series-award-3fbc80c598664d09274cdbe80ed511d5 |url-status=live}}</ref> Sawai also became the first Asian to win her category, while Sanada became the second Asian to do so in his category after [[Lee Jung-jae]] for his role in ''Squid Game'' in 2022.<ref>{{cite news |last=Perez |first=Lexy |title=''Shogun'' Star Anna Sawai Becomes First Actor of Asian Descent to Win Drama Actress Emmy |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/anna-sawai-first-japanese-actress-2024-emmys-1236002354/ |access-date=September 21, 2024 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=September 15, 2024 |archive-date=September 21, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240921072746/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/anna-sawai-first-japanese-actress-2024-emmys-1236002354/ |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Liza Colón-Zayas]] was the first Latina winner for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Comedy Series]] for her performance on ''The Bear''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Victorian |first=Brande |title=''The Bear'' Star Liza Colón-Zayas Becomes First Latina to Win Best Supporting Actress in a Comedy Emmy |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/2024-emmys-best-supporting-actress-comedy-liza-colon-zayas-the-bear-1236002710/ |access-date=September 24, 2024 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=September 15, 2024 |archive-date=September 24, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240924080107/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/2024-emmys-best-supporting-actress-comedy-liza-colon-zayas-the-bear-1236002710/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

Winners are listed first, highlighted in '''boldface''', and indicated with a double dagger (‡).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.televisionacademy.com/files/assets/Downloads/76thnominations-list-v4.pdf |title=76th Emmy Awards Complete Nominations List |publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |access-date=September 19, 2024 |archive-date=September 29, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240929075931/https://www.televisionacademy.com/files/assets/Downloads/76thnominations-list-v4.pdf |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.emmys.com/76th-emmy-winners |title=76th Emmy Awards Winners Announced |date=September 15, 2024 |publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |format=PDF |access-date=September 25, 2024 |archive-date=September 29, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240929075914/https://www.emmys.com/76th-emmy-winners |url-status=live}}</ref>{{efn|The outlets listed for each program are the U.S. broadcasters or streaming services identified in the nominations, which for some international productions are different than the broadcaster(s) that originally [[commission (art)|commissioned]] the program. Programs broadcast by [[HBO]] or [[HBO Max|Max]] were listed under both services in the nominations list; only the original broadcaster is listed below.}} For simplicity, producers who received nominations for program awards have been omitted.

